A '''debubblizer''' is a [[surface tension]] reducing agent that is used to reduce the prevalence of [[Liquid bubble|bubble]]s in industrial processes such as [[wax casting]]{{Ambiguous|date=February 2017}}.

[[Category:Industrial processes]]


{{technology-stub}}

An '''Estoppel Certificate''' (or '''Estoppel Letter''') is a document often used in due diligence in [[Real estate]] and [[Mortgage loan|mortgage]] activities.<ref name="Shaffer">{{cite journal|last1=Shaffer|first1=Brent C.|title=Using Tenant Estoppel Letters to Cut to the Chase|date=2001|url=http://www.americanbar.org/publications/probate_property_magazine_home/rppt_publications_magazine_2001_01nd_shaffer.html|accessdate=3 March 2017|publisher=ABA}}</ref> It is a document often completed, but at least signed, by a tenant used in his or her landlord's proposed transaction with a third party.<ref name=Shaffer/> A mortgage lender intending to collateralize a tenant-occupied property or a purchaser intending to purchase such a property will often want to verify certain representations made by the landlord.<ref name=Shaffer/>
An estoppel certificate provides confirmation by the tenant of the terms of the rental agreement, such as the amount of rent, the amount of security deposit and the expiration of the agreement.<ref name=Shaffer/> Further, the estoppel certificate may give the opportunity to the tenant to explain if they may have any claims against the landlord, which may affect a buyer's or lender's decision to complete the proposed transaction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Definition of Estoppel Certificate|url=http://www.redfin.com/definition/estoppel-certificate|publisher=Redfin}}</ref>
Some lease agreements require the tenant to complete such a certificate or to waive his responses by allowing the landlord to complete the estoppel certificate under certain circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heller|first1=Stu|title=The Landlord Wants You to Sign an Estoppel Certificate?|url=http://www.theleasinglawyer.com/estoppel.html}}</ref>
In some extreme cases, a tenant can be in default of a lease when failing to comply with an estoppel certificate, though this is rare. The majority of leases do not mention the protocol for signature of estoppel certificates.{{cn|date=June 2017}}
